🧠 UNIT OF MEASURES — RECORD VIEW + EXECUTION LAYER SPEC
First Fully Governed Table Under the Record View Engine
🔷 0. PURPOSE

The Unit of Measures (UOM) table is the first system entity to be fully governed by:

* Record View Engine (UI + Controller)
* Execution Layer (Transport → Application → Domain → Data → Infra)

This establishes the canonical pattern for all future tables.
Complexity will increase (work orders, templates, imports) — but the structure never changes.

---

🔷 1. ENTITY DEFINITION

📏 Unit of Measure (UOM)

Represents how quantities are measured across the system.

Fields:
* id
* name (e.g. "Square Feet", "Linear Feet")
* createdAt
* updatedAt

Note: No abbreviation field exists in the current schema. If added later, it passes through the same execution path as name.

---

🔗 Relationships

* A UOM can be linked to Categories (sendUnit, stockUnit, coverageAvailableUnit, itemCoverageUnit, serviceUnit)
* A UOM can be linked to Services
* A UOM can be linked to Template Service Items
* A UOM can be linked to Work Order Service Items
* A UOM CANNOT be deleted if any of these links exist

---

🔴 CRITICAL BUSINESS RULE

❗ A Unit of Measure CANNOT be deleted if it is referenced by any Category or Service record

Ownership of this Rule:
👉 Domain Layer (source of truth)

Enforcement also appears at:
* Application (final guard before mutation, inside transaction)
* Transport (early rejection on known invalid requests)
* Data (FK constraints as a last-resort defensive layer)

---

🔷 2. RECORD VIEW ENGINE STRUCTURE (UOM)

UOM is a single-section record view.
It is simple — but it MUST follow the full engine pattern.
This is what makes it the canonical reference.

Structure:

RecordView: Unit of Measure
  → FieldSection: General (PrimaryRow: UOM)
      Fields: name
      Actions: Save, Delete

Why This Matters:
* UOM uses the SAME engine as complex systems (work orders, templates)
* No special-case UI or shortcut logic
* The engine governs — UOM configures

Note on ChildScopedRows:
UOM has no GridSection and no ChildScopedRows today.
If UOM gains child data in the future (e.g. conversion factors), a GridSection is added.
The engine handles it — no structural change required.

